<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910510-0018</DOCNO><DOCID>910510-0018.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Allegheny Power System Inc.:   Utility Seeks Rate Increase   For Clean Air Compliance</HL><DATE>05/10/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><CO>   AYP</CO><MS>UTILITIES (UTI)</MS><IN>ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)ENVIRONMENT (ENV)</IN><NS>ENVIRONMENTAL NEWS (ENV)</NS><RE>NEW YORK (NY)OHIO (OH)PENNSYLVANIA (PA)WEST VIRGINIA (WV)</RE><LP>   Allegheny Power System Inc. said it is seeking rateincreases of between 6% and 8% over a five year periodstarting 1995 to help fund costs for complying with federalclean-air standards.   The New York electric utility holding company said it willcost about $805 million to comply with Phase 1 acid rainprovisions of the 1990 Clean Air Act, which requires reducingtotal sulfur dioxide emissions by 50%. The utility must be incompliance by Jan. 1, 1995.</LP><TEXT>   Allegheny Power has said it is installing a smokestackscrubbing device at its Harrison plant in Clarksburg, W.Va.At the annual shareholders' meeting yesterday, Klaus Bergman,president, said this was the least costly and most beneficialstrategy for Allegheny Power to comply with the acid rainprovisions.   Partly to cover compliance costs, the company has alreadyfiled for rate increases in Maryland and Virginia, and plansto do so in the three other states it serves -- Pennsylvania,West Virginia and Ohio.</TEXT></DOC>